y: Helvetica;font-size: 15px;line-height: 150%;text-align: left;">1/ I wan=
t to evangelize a 2019 resolution=2C especially for organizations: "let's=
 make things boring".<br>
<br>
2/ The guiding principle is the idea=2C "The opposite of every great truth=
 is also a great truth" -- Niels Bohr.<br>
<br>
3/ "You learn most in direction of maximal interestingness" is a great tru=
th=2C and the driver of innovation.&nbsp;But "You learn most in direction=
 of maximal boringness" is <em>also</em> a great truth=2C and the driver o=
f sustainability at scale.<br>
<br>
4/ The <a href=3D"https://breakingsmart.us1.list-manage.com/track/click?u=
=3D78cbbb7f2882629a5157fa593&id=3Dd1aabd3b13&e=3D4c5a41c2ff" target=3D"_b=
lank" style=3D"word-wrap: break-word;-ms-text-size-adjust: 100%;-webkit-te=
xt-size-adjust: 100%;color: #6DC6DD;font-weight: normal;text-decoration: u=
nderline;">Axios newsletter today</a>&nbsp;has this line about the latest=
 bit of exhausting Trumpery out of Washington=2C DC: "The bottom line: Nor=
ms and precedents are boring. The lack of them is interesting=2C but almos=
t always at a severe cost."<br>
<br>
5/ Arguing for norms might seem a bit conservative=2C reactionary=2C and <=
a href=3D"https://breakingsmart.us1.list-manage.com/track/click?u=3D78cbbb=
7f2882629a5157fa593&id=3Df7b6afcec1&e=3D4c5a41c2ff" target=3D"_blank" sty=
le=3D"word-wrap: break-word;-ms-text-size-adjust: 100%;-webkit-text-size-a=
djust: 100%;color: #6DC6DD;font-weight: normal;text-decoration: underline;=
">Chesterton Fencish</a>=2C but it needn't be. Making things boring is (fo=
r instance) the basic challenge of scaling an innovative technology.<br>
<br>
6/ Seth Godin once said something like "a technology becomes socially inte=
resting when it becomes technologically boring." Making an interesting tec=
hnology boring tends to make engineering reputations.<br>
<br>
7/ If you're running a company with engineering and marketing challenges=
=2C you can't make the marketing interesting until you make the engineerin=
g boring. And you can't make the engineering interesting again till the ma=
rketing gets boring enough to drive a firehose of cash.<br>
<br>
8/ On the more philosophical end=2C there's that line from A. N. Whitehead=
=2E "civilization advances by extending the number of important operations w=
hich we can perform without thinking of them." Making things boring is abo=
ut <em>locking in progress</em>.<br>
<br>
9/ We focus a lot on the abuse/discarding of norms these days=2C with the=
 lament=2C "this is not normal." You make things interesting by flouting o=
ld norms. You make things boring by installing new norms.<br>
<br>
10/ Cults and alt realities rise to prominence by being interesting=2C but=
 establish themselves as "normal" for the long term by deliberately becomi=
ng boring. That's the "institutional" in institutional religion. As I twee=
ted once=2C "normalcy is merely the majority sect of magical thinking."<br=
>
<br>
11/ If you stop at flouting/breaking old norms=2C you'll vanish like a fla=
sh flood leaving no trace behind. Old norms will just come creeping back.=
 Chesterton's fence will rebuild itself.<br>
<br>
12/ Why? People lack imagination. In the absence of a new norm=2C they'll=
 revert to an old norm. That's a good thing. Old norms backstop half-assed=
 experiments in novelty that fail or are abandoned.&nbsp;<br>
<br>
13/&nbsp;The other half of the equation=2C "normalizing" new things=2C can=
 be&nbsp;the scary part when the things that people are seeking to normali=
ze seem cruel=2C unjust=2C&nbsp;or awful in some way. You do not want "be=
 cruel to children and animals" to be a new societal "norm."<br>
<br>
14/ But we&nbsp;often conflate&nbsp;being in a numb/jaded/exhausted/burnt=
 out state due to repeated trauma or transgression with "normalizing" thin=
gs that shouldn't be normalized. Numbness is not "normalization."<br>
<br>
15/ The joke "the beatings will continue until morale improves" gets at wh=
y mere repetition of a transgression of an old norm to exhaust the capacit=
y to respond&nbsp;is (fortunately) not a way to install a new norm. You ca=
n't beat generativity and growth out of people.<br>
<br>
16/ A real norm is self-enforcing without much coercive energy. If "beatin=
g" is needed=2C it's not a norm=2C it's a negatively incentivized&nbsp;beh=
avior. A real norm gets installed in our superegos. The incentives are int=
ernal. The carrots and sticks are inside our heads.<br>
<br>
17/ We feel guilt and/or shame at transgressing it&nbsp;even if nobody is=
 watching=2C let alone beating us. If we are tempted into transgression=2C=
 we have the decency to at least try and cover it up. That's a good thing=
=2C even though it can seem like condoning hypocrisy.<br>
<br>
18/ The presence of hypocrisy around a norm in a society shows it&nbsp;sti=
ll has power. That there are consequences to breaking it. Not just legal o=
nes=2C or shaming by others=2C but <em>internal</em> consequences we infli=
ct on ourselves=2C via guilt.&nbsp;<br>
<br>
19/ The Trump era has numbed us to a lot of things=2C but it hasn't actual=
ly <em>normalized</em> any awful new behaviors that weren't already normal=
ized. So far=2C "this is not normal" hasn't been a necessary chant=2C even=
 though it has been a common one. That's the good news.<br>
<br>
20/ There's been a few wannabe ugly-new-norm-normalizers in the Trump crow=
d (such as Stephen Miller) but they've had low impact at the norms level o=
utside of regulatory hacks/de-institutionalization efforts. Good things th=
ey destroy can be rebuilt.<br>
<br>
21/ Fortunately for our collective sanity=2C it still isn't "normal" to be=
 cruel to children. Pussy-grabbing hasn't replaced hand-shaking as a way f=
or men to greet women socially. Despite all the reactionary moral panic ar=
ound the #metoo movement=2C men and women haven't actually stopped hooking=
 up=2C dating=2C or getting married.<br>
<br>
22/ To make things boring is to look for areas in need of norms=2C and wor=
king to install them. In 2019=2C we especially need "make it boring" effor=
ts in the cultural sphere (though of course=2C by all means pursue it in o=
ther areas too). Every culture war dumpster fire is an opportunity for an=
 imaginative effort to install a new norm.&nbsp;<br>
<br>
23/ So as you look for opportunities to make things boring in 2019=2C look=
 at where there are dumpster fires=2C charged emotions=2C flaming conflict=
s=2C etc. The immediate goal is to put out the fires. The long-term goal i=
s to make things less flammable. <em>A good norm makes it easier to be goo=
d than evil=2C for your value of "good" and "evil."</em><br>
<br>
24/ Here is <a href=3D"https://breakingsmart.us1.list-manage.com/track/cli=
ck?u=3D78cbbb7f2882629a5157fa593&id=3Da1448c6801&e=3D4c5a41c2ff" target=
=3D"_blank" style=3D"word-wrap: break-word;-ms-text-size-adjust: 100%;-web=
kit-text-size-adjust: 100%;color: #6DC6DD;font-weight: normal;text-decorat=
ion: underline;">a brilliant&nbsp;example</a> of a kindergarten teacher wo=
rking imaginatively to install a better norm around consent and bodily aut=
onomy in children. She simply has the children pick their preferred mornin=
g greeting out of 4 options (a hug=2C a high-five=2C a little dance=2C or=
 a handshake)&nbsp;as they enter class. That's an A+.<br>
<br>
25/ Contrast this with the unimaginative moral-panic mongering in this cas=
e of <a href=3D"https://breakingsmart.us1.list-manage.com/track/click?u=3D=
78cbbb7f2882629a5157fa593&id=3D677859c7f7&e=3D4c5a41c2ff" target=3D"_blan=
k" style=3D"word-wrap: break-word;-ms-text-size-adjust: 100%;-webkit-text-=
size-adjust: 100%;color: #6DC6DD;font-weight: normal;text-decoration: unde=
rline;">a mom pretending her adult son in the Navy is too scared to date b=
ecause of fear of harassment accusations</a> (the son later stridently dis=
avowed his mother's claims). That's an F.<br>
<br>
26/&nbsp;There's an obvious playbook to installing good norms and making n=
ew&nbsp;behaviors normal=2C boring=2C and most importantly=2C not-shameful=
=2E The only tricky ingredient is imagination. Yes=2C like the kindergarten=
 teacher above=2C you need imagination to make things boring=2C oddly enou=
gh.<br>
<br>
27/ You can't do it to all behaviors. A&nbsp;pre-normalization reasonablen=
ess test applies. This is a good thing. We humans -- well most of us -- do=
 have an innate sense of when a behavior we're being encouraged to adopt i=
s cruel=2C unfair=2C or self-serving=2C and if not=2C are able to see it w=
hen pointed out. We're not morons.<br>
<br>
28/ Despite all the pearl-clutching moral panic around #metoo for instance=
=2C nobody I know thinks the theatrical Mike Pence norm&nbsp;of never meet=
ing with women 1 on 1 or in private is a good one. It's a sort of injured=
 conservative martyrdom virtue signaling via a strawman norm.<br>
<br>
29/ It fails the reasonableness test on multiple levels. It's unfair to wo=
men to be excluded from productive opportunities for 1:1 interaction or pr=
ivate conversations. It's toxic to embed the belief that all men are poten=
tial harassers into the environment. And worst of all: it doesn't actually=
 solve the problem. Sexual harassers will find a way.<br>
<br>
30/&nbsp;It's idiotic to design a norm around worst-case expectations ("co=
rner cases make bad law" applies to norm design as well). Not surprisingly=
=2C the reports of the norm being adopted are mostly emerging from sectors=
 that already have an awful reputation for sexism=2C like finance.<br>
<br>
31/ But assuming you have an idea for a norm that seems reasonable (good t=
est: run it by a representative set of the people who would actually have=
 to adopt it)=2C there's a&nbsp;design-and-installation playbook of sorts=
=2C with 8 basic rules. Here they are:<br>
<br>
<strong>8 Rules for Designing and Installing Norms</strong></p>

<ol>
=09<li style=3D"-ms-text-size-adjust: 100%;-webkit-text-size-adjust: 100%;=
"><u><em>Make it unskilled:</em></u> it should be no extra mental effort t=
o practice the norm</li>
=09<li style=3D"-ms-text-size-adjust: 100%;-webkit-text-size-adjust: 100%;=
"><u><em>Make it self-reinforcing</em></u>: it should be habit forming</li=
>
=09<li style=3D"-ms-text-size-adjust: 100%;-webkit-text-size-adjust: 100%;=
"><u><em>Automate it</em></u>: let machines do the difficult parts where p=
ossible</li>
=09<li style=3D"-ms-text-size-adjust: 100%;-webkit-text-size-adjust: 100%;=
"><u><em>Take heroism/villainy out of it</em></u>: his is a crucial thing=
=2C nobody wants to be a hero or risk being called a villain every day.</l=
i>
=09<li style=3D"-ms-text-size-adjust: 100%;-webkit-text-size-adjust: 100%;=
"><u><em>Make it visible and imitable</em></u>: norms don't spread through=
 lecturing=2C they spread through imitation. The visibility implies there=
 should be no shame to it=2C which "bad" candidate norms will generally fa=
il. Imitability means seeing it done should be enough to figure out how to=
 do it=2C even if you're neurotypically disadvantaged when it comes to&nbs=
p;picking up on social cues.</li>
=09<li style=3D"-ms-text-size-adjust: 100%;-webkit-text-size-adjust: 100%;=
"><u><em>Make it microkarmic</em></u>: 1 recycled can =3D&nbsp;1 whuffie o=
f feeling good about it even if nobody sees you do it. This simply means m=
ild short-term positive reinforcement.</li>
=09<li style=3D"-ms-text-size-adjust: 100%;-webkit-text-size-adjust: 100%;=
"><u><em>Unbrand it</em></u>: turn secret handshakes into ordinary ones. Y=
ou don't get premium extra points for recycling soda cans when everybody d=
oes. Behaving a certain way shouldn't mark you as a member of a special cl=
ub.</li>
=09<li style=3D"-ms-text-size-adjust: 100%;-webkit-text-size-adjust: 100%;=
"><u><em>Uncode it</em></u>: the virtue signaling&nbsp;value of a good nor=
m should be zero. Norms aren't and shouldn't be currencies. The behavior s=
hould not "signal" that you profess/practice an exceptional=2C saintly vir=
tue. It should not become a way for saints to connect in mutual admiration=
=2E</li>
</ol>

<p style=3D"margin: 1em 0;padding: 0;-ms-text-size-adjust: 100%;-webkit-te=
xt-size-adjust: 100%;color: #606060;font-family: Helvetica;font-size: 15px=
;line-height: 150%;text-align: left;">32/ If you successfully do these 8 t=
hings=2C it will become part of background social infrastructure that is s=
elf-regulating=2C self-socializing etc. It will also drain the culture-war=
 energy out of the behavior and any counter-behaviors. Suck the air out=2C=
 starve the dumpster fire flames.<br>
<br>
33/ Remember=2C ultimately=2C "making things boring" is about making it ea=
sier to be good than bad. That's all a norm really is. A way for civilizat=
ion to advance by making it less effort to behave in more advanced ways. I=
t's not an attempt to limit or constrain your behavior. It's a mechanism t=
o enable more advanced behaviors.</p>

